"I thought I saw my own worst enemy, a kind of demon. And it was me."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utwotribes.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Twotribes</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Troll</span><br>  Posts: 206<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/15/02 5:45:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1122.topic&index=9>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A big problem with EQ - Individuality</span><hr size=1> One problem with mass market games and different path choices is the fact that unless the game spells out in very clear and definate terms what you gain and lose on EVERY major path, people will become irritated when they find their chosen path is a backwater one.<br>
<br>
UO has/had many choices..... problem is some are so much more powerful then others you lose out in game if you dont follow the several power paths.<br>
<br>
Now with more amd more games being thought up and possibly becoming fact, this could change.  But just look at the screams of complaint with only ... what 14 classes. Everyone thinks they got slighted in someway and some other class is better.<br>
<br>
In a game that lives or dies by the money it pulls in (meaning attracting people) few will risk going to far astray from what is known to work.  I would say EQ learned from UO to limit class choices.<br>
<br>
Even with just 14 classes you still see the rants about this class is the best, this is the worst. When you depend on others to group with you dont want to many unknowns (or so the process goes in the minds of the money men and the dimbulbs that let prejuidice rule their lives)<br>
<br>
Give it time and keep on coming up with ideas like this. Sooner or later someone WILL try it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=kendrikfv>kendrik fv</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/15/02 6:20:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1122.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The good, the bad, and UO</span><hr size=1> Say what you will about UO, one of it's greatest strengths was the ability to find your own niche and be YOU. UO had individuality written all over it. Sure, if you wanted to be the shard's best pk or anti, your choices were narrowed down some. But there were lots of players who were abundantly happy roleplaying a cook, or wandering healer dressed only in a robe and carrying some food and a pile of bandages.<br>
<br>
On Lake Superior, I was the guild treasure hunter. The guild was one of the more powerful anti guilds, House al Nasir (HaN), but everyone knew I was available to locate buried treasure for anyone as long as they cut me in for a share. I was highly specialized and extremely individual but I made people lots of gold and magic items. I was dead meat if even one mob from a level 2 chest got hold of me, but the rest of the group knew that and I had ways of making sure they didn't get me. I treasure hunted for some of the best pk's on the shard and when I quit, I had millions of gold, a couple of houses, and tons of good magic loot (I lost count how many silver heavy xbows vanquishing I had). My point is, as Alpha Khan (my treasure hunter) I could not pvp or pvm at all, but I had a blast and did quite well. That kind of choice just does not exist in EQ and I miss it.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ufeneant.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Feneant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 256<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 12:22:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1122.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The good, the bad, and UO</span><hr size=1> They pass Everquest off as a game where you can take a trade skills and make a living from it, but you would get bored within minutes of trying to do this, you can only hawke banded so long before you get bored...<br>
<br>
Other than player indivuality, I would like to see Skill individuality (and not cultural armor).  I would like the skills to be a lot more varied so that someone might discovver how to make an item that others would never be able to do.  Doesn't Horizons plan on having something like this?  <br>
<br>
As it is now, we all start off with a template, get to 60 and become a higher level template but that's all everyone is, just a template, some might do a bit more damage, but others might have more defense, other than that, everyone in a class is playing a clone of someone else.<br>
<br>
From my point of view , Everquest doesn't even have room for changing this... to add more skills and such would just imbalance the game... there are no npc's asking you to make items for them, there are no dynamic quest to yeild items that no one else has (except the ubers), there are no difference whatsoever in skills, so really no way that they could implement individuality short of completely revamping the skills and making it so that only hardcore people could actually master one and that all masters would be different, like some in armor, common weapons or magic items... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uwyntercrystalbow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wynter Crystalbow</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 79<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 4:34:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1122.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hmmm...</span><hr size=1> Well, I suppose I have to agree.  The only way to be individual in EQ is a player's play style.  Any enchanter can tell you that if they've made it past 20.  Though I've noticed some of the newer games trying to implement it.  DAoC seems from what I've seen of it a skill system, though I don't know of any general utility skills so if you don't max a skill out you pretty much get screwed later on.  Shadowbane has been in development for years and with it's large number of class/discipline combinations it seems to follow a pseudo EQ/pseudo UO line.  However balancing is going to be a pain in the rear.  It's why EQ is the way it is.  EQ was developed so that one class or another was any more powerful than another in theory, that even if you made a bad choice you could correct it.  No game is perfect *shrug* <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><